----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------0. | Punya Prasun Bajpai (born 18 March 1963) is an Indian journalist, a figure whose career has spanned decades across the evolving landscape of Indian electronic and print media. His distinctive approach to news delivery and analysis has made him a recognizable, if sometimes controversial, presence in the national discourse.

### Early life

Punya Prasun Bajpai was born on 18 March 1963, in [Muzaffarpur](/Muzaffarpur), a prominent city in the vibrant state of [Bihar](/Bihar), India. His formative years were influenced by his father, the late Mani Kant Bajpai, who served as an esteemed officer in the IIS ([Indian Information Service](/Indian_Information_Service)). This familial connection to public service and information dissemination likely provided an early, if subconscious, introduction to the world Bajpai would later inhabit. His foundational education was completed at Kendriya Vidyalaya, Kankarbagh, Patna, a common educational pathway in India. He then pursued higher studies, graduating with honors in Political Science from Bihar National College, Patna, a background that would undoubtedly inform his future journalistic endeavors and his keen understanding of political dynamics.

### Career

Bajpai commenced his extensive journey in the electronic media realm with [Aaj Tak](/Aaj_Tak) in 1996, a period that marked the nascent stages of 24-hour news television in India. He remained with the channel until 2003, establishing himself as a significant voice. Following this initial tenure, he transitioned to [NDTV](/NDTV), where he contributed for a period of fourteen months, further diversifying his experience within the competitive news environment.

His leadership capabilities were recognized when he assumed the role of Editor-in-Chief at Sahara Samay during 2007–2008, a critical position that involves shaping the editorial direction and content strategy of a major news outlet. Subsequently, Bajpai spent four years at [Zee News](/Zee_News), serving as both a prime-time anchor and editor, a dual responsibility that placed him at the forefront of daily news delivery and editorial decision-making. His notable program during this time was "Badi Khabar." It seems the gravitational pull of his earlier professional home was strong, as he eventually returned to [Aaj Tak](/Aaj_Tak). During this second stint, he became particularly renowned for hosting the popular weekday show known as *DusTak* (often stylized as *10 तक*), a program that became a staple for many viewers seeking in-depth news analysis and commentary.

In April 2018, Bajpai embarked on a new chapter, joining [ABP News](/ABP_News) to host *Masterstroke*, a prime-time offering that quickly garnered attention. However, this tenure proved to be remarkably brief, lasting only four months. He tendered his resignation on 1 August 2018, a departure widely attributed to alleged political pressure exerted upon the news channel, a narrative that resonated deeply within the Indian media fraternity.

The journalistic odyssey continued in February 2019, when he took on the mantle of Editor-in-Chief at [Surya Samachar](/Surya_Samachar), where he also helmed the shows *Jai Hind* and *Satta*. This, too, was a temporary engagement, as he later departed from Surya Samachar.

Bajpai's influence extends beyond television screens. In 2015, his active engagement on social media platforms was noted, positioning him as one of the ten most active Indian journalists on [Twitter](/Twitter). Recognizing the shifting tides of media consumption and the increasing importance of independent platforms, he launched his own news channel on [YouTube](/YouTube) in 2019. This move allowed him to maintain a direct connection with his audience, free from the perceived constraints and pressures of traditional corporate media houses. As of June 19, 2025, his [YouTube channel](/YouTube_channel_(identifier)) boasts a substantial following of 5.2 million subscribers and has amassed an impressive 1.4 billion views, underscoring his continued relevance and reach in the digital age. His career, spanning over 29 years, is a testament to his enduring presence and adaptability across various reputed media agencies, including early stints in print with [Jansatta](/Jansatta), Sunday Observer, Sunday Mail, and [Lokmat](/Lokmat), alongside his extensive work in electronic media at [Zee News](/Zee_News) and [NDTV](/NDTV).

### Publications

Beyond his extensive work in broadcast journalism, Bajpai has also contributed significantly to the literary landscape, penning six books that delve into various facets of Indian society, politics, and media. His published works include:

*   *राजनीति मेरी जान* (Raajneeti Meri Jaan)
*   *डिजास्टरः मीडिया एंड पॉलिटिक्स* (Disaster: Media and Politics)
*   *संसदः लोकतंत्र या नजरों का धोखा* (Sansad: Loktantra ya nazron ka dhokha)
*   *आदिवासियों पर टाडा* (Aadivasiyon par TADA)
*   *R.S.S. Sangh Ka Safar: 100 varsh*

These titles reflect his analytical depth and critical perspective on contemporary issues. In addition to his book-length works, Bajpai regularly contributes articles to a diverse range of daily and weekly news and literary publications in Hindi. Many of these insightful pieces are also made accessible to a broader audience through his personal blog, further solidifying his presence as a prolific commentator and author.

### Awards

Punya Prasun Bajpai has received notable recognition for his contributions to journalism, a testament to his impactful reporting and unwavering dedication.

*   His exceptional work during the harrowing [2001 Indian Parliament attack](/2001_Indian_Parliament_attack) earned him significant commendation. During this critical national event, he anchored live for five consecutive hours, providing continuous and vital information to the public under immense pressure. This particular feat highlighted his composure and journalistic mettle in a crisis.
*   He is also a distinguished recipient of the prestigious [Ramnath Goenka](/Ramnath_Goenka) Award for Excellence in Journalism. He received this honor for his work in Hindi print and electronic media, first in the 2005–06 cycle and again in 2007–08. This dual recognition is particularly noteworthy, as Bajpai holds the unique distinction of being the only journalist to have received this esteemed award in both television and print categories twice. The image of him receiving the award from then-Prime Minister, Dr. Manmohan Singh in 2006, serves as a public acknowledgment of his significant achievements.

### Controversy

Bajpai's career, like that of many prominent journalists operating in a politically charged environment, has not been without its share of controversies, raising questions about journalistic integrity and the pressures faced by the media.

#### Arvind Kejriwal Interview (2014)

In March 2014, a leaked video surfaced that ignited a significant debate, often dubbed "media fixing." The footage showed Bajpai in an interview with [Arvind Kejriwal](/Arvind_Kejriwal), then a rising political figure. During this interaction, Bajpai appeared to be receiving instructions from Kejriwal regarding the promotion of his interview. Specifically, Kejriwal allegedly directed Bajpai to frame his resignation in a manner that would compare it to the sacrifice of [Bhagat Singh](/Bhagat_Singh), a revered Indian revolutionary. Furthermore, Kejriwal reportedly instructed Bajpai to omit a certain portion of the interview concerning the privatization of industries, presumably to avoid portraying himself as anti-middle class.

When the interview was subsequently telecast, it was observed that Bajpai had indeed complied with these alleged instructions. This perceived adherence to a politician's agenda rather than maintaining editorial independence sparked widespread criticism and raised serious questions about his journalistic ethics and the integrity of the media landscape at large. The incident became a flashpoint in discussions about the relationship between politicians and journalists, and the potential for manipulation in news reporting.

#### ABP News 'Masterstroke' and Allegations of Political Pressure (2018)

Bajpai's tenure as host of the prime-time show *Masterstroke* on [ABP News](/ABP_News) was abruptly cut short amidst another high-profile controversy in July 2018. The channel faced considerable criticism, reportedly from the government, following a story aired on *Masterstroke*. This particular segment focused on a video interaction that took place on 20 June 2018, between [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_India) Mr. [Narendra Modi](/Narendra_Modi) and beneficiaries of various government programs.

The *Masterstroke* report highlighted the case of Chandramani Kaushik, a participant from [Chhattisgarh](/Chhattisgarh), who had told Prime Minister Modi on the official show that her income had ostensibly doubled after she shifted from cultivating paddy to growing custard apples. However, two weeks later, based on subsequent investigations, *ABP News Masterstroke* claimed that Ms. Kaushik had allegedly been tutored by officials from the ruling BJP to make these false claims during her interaction with the Prime Minister.

Following the broadcast of this critical report, [ABP News](/ABP_News) reportedly experienced unusual technical difficulties. Specifically, the channel's satellite link began to "misbehave" during the airing of Bajpai's program. In an article penned by Bajpai himself for [The Wire](/The_Wire_(Indian_web_publication)), he explicitly stated that some prominent advertisers, including the consumer goods giant [Patanjali](/Patanjali_Ayurved), subsequently withdrew their advertisements from the channel. Bajpai contended that under the immense pressure generated by these circumstances – the alleged technical interference and the loss of advertising revenue – he was compelled to resign from the channel. This incident underscored the precarious position of independent journalism in India and the perceived consequences of reporting critically on powerful political figures.

